{
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# 10 Transformer and Sequence Model Architectures\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook gives a clear overview of 10 architectures that are often compared with or used instead of classic Seq2Seq.\n",
        "\n",
        "It includes:\n",
        "- what each architecture is\n",
        "- where it is used\n",
        "- why it matters\n",
        "- a simple example\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Quick comparison\n",
        "\n",
        "| # | Architecture | Main idea | Best for |\n",
        "|---|---|---|---|\n",
        "| 1 | Encoder-only | Understand input text | Classification, embeddings |\n",
        "| 2 | Decoder-only | Predict next token | Chat, generation |\n",
        "| 3 | Encoder + Retrieval (RAG) | Search external knowledge first | Factual QA |\n",
        "| 4 | Sparse Transformer | Attend to only some tokens | Long documents |\n",
        "| 5 | Mixture of Experts (MoE) | Activate only selected experts | Large scalable models |\n",
        "| 6 | State Space Model (SSM) | Use evolving memory/state | Very long sequences |\n",
        "| 7 | CNN-based NLP | Capture local patterns | Fast text classification |\n",
        "| 8 | RNN / LSTM | Process tokens step by step | Simple sequence tasks |\n",
        "| 9 | Hybrid architectures | Combine multiple ideas | Special use cases |\n",
        "| 10 | Diffusion-based text models | Iterative denoising generation | Experimental text generation |\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 1. Encoder-only architecture\n",
        "Encoder-only models read the full input and build deep contextual representations.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "`Input -> Encoder -> Output`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- text classification\n",
        "- sentiment analysis\n",
        "- named entity recognition\n",
        "- semantic embeddings\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "Input: `\"I love this movie\"`\n",
        "\n",
        "Output: `Positive`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "It is usually faster and simpler than Seq2Seq when you only need to understand text, not generate it.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 2. Decoder-only architecture\n",
        "Decoder-only models generate text one token at a time.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "`Input tokens -> Decoder -> Next token`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- chatbots\n",
        "- text generation\n",
        "- code generation\n",
        "- instruction following\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "Input: `\"The sky is\"`\n",
        "\n",
        "Output: `blue`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "This is the architecture behind many modern large language models because it scales well for generation.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 3. Encoder + Retrieval (RAG)\n",
        "Retrieval-Augmented Generation combines search with generation.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "`Query -> Retriever -> Relevant documents -> Generator`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- question answering\n",
        "- enterprise chatbots\n",
        "- document search systems\n",
        "- reducing hallucinations\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "Question: `\"What is the refund policy?\"`\n",
        "\n",
        "The system retrieves the policy document first, then writes the answer.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "It helps the model answer with external facts instead of relying only on memory.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 4. Sparse Transformer\n",
        "Sparse Transformers reduce the number of attention links.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "Instead of every token attending to every other token, each token attends only to selected tokens.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- long documents\n",
        "- books\n",
        "- long-context tasks\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "A token may attend only to nearby words and a few global tokens.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "It lowers memory and compute cost compared with full attention.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 5. Mixture of Experts (MoE)\n",
        "MoE models contain multiple expert sub-networks, but only some are activated for each token.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "`Token -> Router -> Selected Experts -> Output`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- very large models\n",
        "- efficient scaling\n",
        "- high-capacity NLP systems\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "One expert may handle code-like text while another handles conversation-like text.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "It allows huge parameter counts without using all parameters at once.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 6. State Space Model (SSM)\n",
        "SSMs use a changing internal state to process sequences efficiently.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "`Current input + previous state -> new state -> output`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- very long sequences\n",
        "- streaming data\n",
        "- speech/audio\n",
        "- efficient inference\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "A model reads a long document while continuously updating memory.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "It can be much more memory-efficient than full attention for long inputs.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 7. CNN-based NLP architecture\n",
        "CNNs detect local patterns in text using convolution filters.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "`Text -> Convolution filters -> Feature maps -> Classifier`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- sentence classification\n",
        "- keyword detection\n",
        "- fast pattern matching\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "A filter may detect phrases like `very good` or `not bad`.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "It is simple, fast, and works well for local patterns.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 8. RNN / LSTM architecture\n",
        "RNNs and LSTMs process tokens in order, one step at a time.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "`x1 -> x2 -> x3 -> ...`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- small sequence tasks\n",
        "- simpler time-series or text pipelines\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "The model reads a sentence token by token and updates hidden memory.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "They are conceptually simple, though slower and weaker than Transformers for many NLP tasks.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 9. Hybrid architectures\n",
        "Hybrid architectures combine multiple ideas, such as attention plus retrieval or CNN plus Transformer.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "The exact design depends on the task.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- specialized NLP systems\n",
        "- multimodal systems\n",
        "- systems needing memory or speed trade-offs\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "A system may use retrieval for facts and a Transformer for generation.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "Hybrids can balance speed, accuracy, memory, and flexibility.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 10. Diffusion-based text models\n",
        "Diffusion-based text models generate text through iterative refinement or denoising.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Structure\n",
        "`Noise -> repeated refinement -> final text`\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best for\n",
        "- experimental generation methods\n",
        "- research on new generative models\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example\n",
        "The model starts with a rough token sequence and improves it step by step.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why use it?\n",
        "This is an active research direction that may offer different trade-offs from autoregressive decoding.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Final takeaway\n",
        "\n",
        "If the goal is:\n",
        "- **understanding text** \u2192 encoder-only\n",
        "- **generating text** \u2192 decoder-only\n",
        "- **finding facts and answering from documents** \u2192 RAG\n",
        "- **very long sequences** \u2192 sparse attention or SSMs\n",
        "- **specialized systems** \u2192 hybrids or MoE\n"
      ]
    }
  ],
